description.text: This is a replacement Gocupi gondola that will accept pens up to 25 mm in diameter. It uses plastic bearings with glass balls and a servo attached to the bottom.

Final assembly

Plastic bearings with glass balls are pushed into the bearing rings. The bearings are available here:

http://www.ebay.com/itm/400241248951

Small screws or glue are used to attach the extension arms to the bearing rings. Small holes are drilled on the ends of the extension arms and 2mm screws/nuts are used for connection to the threads from the stepper motors. To assemble all the parts, a bearing spacer is pushed on the central cylinder of the base. That's followed by an extension arm/bearing assembly. Use the arm with the lesser bend to it. A second bearing spacer is next followed by the second extension arm/bearing assembly. Use the arm with the greater bend to it. See the exploded-view image to see the orientation of each extension arm. A servo motor is screwed to the bottom posts of the gondola base.
SketchUp 2017 was used to design all these parts.

i made this mount to fit dual e3d v6 clone hotend's on to my cheap ctc prusa i3 pro b with this X-carriage http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1329854 by Sectorix. I had been using https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:617691 by Triggerr and loved it, so thought id try and remix. The cover has a hole for a 12mm inductive sensor (it's a tight squeeze but does fit), and 2 5mm LED lights, and a 40mm fan. I pointed the ducts up to reduce drafts onto the prints. I still use the GT2560 clone board that came with my printer which has the atmega1280 chip (works well except for the lack of memory). To get dual extruder settings to fit and bed leveling to fit in the memory i had to shut off PID temp and go with Bang Bang heating.

8/19/17
Added picture of fan installed, I have learned that if using PLA you should definitely cover the hotend with at least cotton insulation so the fan duct doesn't warp on your first layer without fan or when you're print finish's. I still haven't created the servo with touch sensor yet but it's on my to-do list

description.text:
Inverted door switch, like the one you can see in Fridge.
I have used it to automatically turn on the lights in my wardrobe. Print have holes for wires, and require additional soldering on top of the printed parts:

  • Glue conductive element on top of the piston jacket
  • Solder output wire to conductive element
  • Solder second wire to conductive element in a piston (I used my Girlfriend Hairpin)
  • Add a spring (I used ball-pen spring) inside the piston Jacket
  • Connect Base with Piston Jacket
  • Insert Piston into a spring-loaded Jacket
  • Put in conductive element (Hairpin part in my case) into a piston pre-made holes to secure Piston inside the jacket so it will create a stopper that will close the circuit

And this is it, you are ready to use it as an inverted button in a project of your choice. You can use Base 90 degree angle to screw it into your door or a closet. (Please let me know in a comment section if you want to have straight mount option instead of corner mount)

(TIP -- use it on the inner part of the door, the one that closer to the hinges. This will avoid false triggering)

title: Chawan (teabowl) modeled after a raku bowl

description.text:
This is a teabowl modeled after a Japanese raku chawan for tea ceremony. This bowl has been printed and tested.

The teabowl has a rounded rim, a kodai that it is easy to grip and a chadamari. It is also slightly wider at the bottom than at the top to make it easier to whisk the tea. It is 100% flat on the top so the chashaku will slide, just like on regular chawan that is flat.

I used regular PLA, not certified food-safe or dishwasher safe, just plain PLA. The teabowl could handle all the water needed for both usucha (thin tea) and koicha (thick tea) temae without becoming soft or deforming.

Please make considerations about food-safety when using a teabowl like this. I would recommend getting food-safe material. However also keep in mind that real raku would not pass a modern criteria for food-safety. In-fact in japan they are exempt from it because the "food" is in contact with the tea bowl for such a short time.

I put glue stick on the build surface. I printed this in PLA.

The handle needs supports to print this. My slicer (Slic3r) does not allow me to customize supports, therefore I had the dilemna of removing unwanted supports from the penny area, as I paused the print.

To remove the print from the build plate, I inserted a strong metal rod into the keychain hole, and used leverage to pry the print loose. The metal rod that I used is nearly the same diameter as the hole.

The trowel handle is not strong enough to pry the print off of the build plate, so use caution.
I use Blender. The trowel shape (blade and handle) is based upon a photo of an antique trowel that is published at http://trowelcollector.blogspot.com/2014/04/.

description.text:
These Items are designed to allow you to test and measure the maximum speed that your printer can successfully print at.
They are:
20mm Square 10mm high rectangle with 1.2mm walls and .5mm floor

50mm Square 10mm high rectangle with 1.2mm walls and .5mm floor

150mm Diameter Cylinder 10mm high

To use these bring one into your favorite slicer and set you speed at whatever speed you want to test and print them. I suggest you use .25 layer height to get the best results from a .4mm nozzle.

To measure your actual average speed pick a spot or corner and use a stopwatch to check each pass several times to find out how long each pass takes. Then you can compare the actual time to the expected time.

If you set your slicer to 100mm/sec for the 150mm circle each pass should occur in 4.71 seconds.
The 50mm Square each pass should occur in 2 seconds.
The 20mm Square each pass should occur in .8 seconds

Each level with a .4mm nozzle will have 3 passes so you could measure level to level if that is easier.

Each of these items test your machine for different situations. The 20mm square test your actual maximum speed for small detailed parts. The 50mm Square test for average sized parts, The 150mm Circle test the actual top speed of your printer.

You can then use this information to create ideal slicer settings for your future prints based on what you are printing.

There are 2 primary failures that can occur with this test. In one case your printer may not be able to hold accurate dimensions, 20mm, 50mm, or 150mm. The other case is your extruder may not be able to extrude the plastic fast enough and you will get skipping and underextrusion.

EDIT: I changed out the 150mm Circle because the original did not print well at all. I would suggest the following settings: 3 Perimeters, 0 top layers, 0 bottom layers, 0 infill. If you have bed adhesion issues try a skirt to see if it helps.

title: Micro Adjustable Bare Wire Z End Stop
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: This is a micro-adjustable bare-wire end stop for reprap printers (or any other machine that could use it). You can also just glue a switch to the top of it if you don't like the bare wire idea. It attaches to the Prusa end stop holder, and is assembled with a spring, M3-30 screw, nut, and washer. A twisted pair set from an old network cable is exposed atop an adjustable surface and makes contact with another bare wire on the X end. This endstop is ridiculously inexpensive, and it allows very fine adjustment of the Z stopping position by turning knob at the bottom -- one full revolution is 0.5mm. I have the OpenSCAD sources for this, and there are actually a number of adjustable parameters. I need to clean the code up a bit and then I'll add it. You can find my basic "one penny" bare wire end stops here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:23878

1) Print the three parts. (It's pretty quick.) 2) Assemble the adjustable end stop. (Refer to picture.) There is a base, a knob, and a cap. The base is the part that clips onto the end stop. Drill out the holes on all three parts if necessary so the screw slides though easily. Melt an M3 nut into the knob with a soldering iron. Place the screw through the top of the cap, then put a spring onto the screw, and then add the base. Orient the cap so that the guide rail slides along the bottom (usually smoother) side of the base. Add a washer or two, and screw the knob onto the exposed end of the screw. The knob hides the end of the screw as is adjusted. Be sure the parts move freely, and clean them up a bit if they don't. Kapton tape can help it slide if necessary. 3) Wire it up. If you want to use bare wires, drill tiny holes (e.g. #60) through the side of the cap, on either side of the screw near the base. Notch the ridges at the top of the cap with a file to accept the wire. Loop wire through holes, over the top, and then tie them off where the entered the sides. (Refer to photo.) 4) Install it. Be sure your hardware is set to use a NO (normally open) end stop for this axis. Fasten a bit of exposed copper wire to the X end and be sure that the wires on the end stop come into contact with it as it drops. (Refer to photo.) Use electrical tape to take up slack if it doesn't fit snugly. Wrap the wire around the end stop holder for stability. 5) Enjoy your ridiculously inexpensive, wildly accurate, and finely adjustable Z end stop. :) I haven't had to yet, but you'll probably need to clean the wires every once in a while. A quick scrape with fine sandpaper will probably do the trick.

description.text:
This is a Y-Rod holder with endstop for the AM8 upgrade that is compatible with the reprap champion carriage for the Anet A8

It brings the endstop forward 10mm and leaves a 2mm safety distance from the y motor mount. This is the same safety distance as the original carriage.

I would recommend only setting your printer's y build volume to 210mm. This leaves a 2mm safety gap from the original A8's slide bushings from hitting the front extrusion.

With the default 220mm bed at a 210 mm build volume, I recommend setting your (0,0) point 5mm from the front of the bed by sliding the side extrusions into a position that allows it and then setting it in your firmware. This will setup correctly centered prints.

Sincde PLA is not soluble in acteone I was looking into alternative ways to get a smooth surface.
One way that leads to maybe a more artistic than practical result is to use molten PLA itself.
I call it PLA-burndropping.
Read the Instructions to see why.

Take a piece of black PLA (3mm diam). Transparent PLA works too (but soft PLA doesn't !)
Prepare a fireproof base & your thing to coat.
Set the tip on fire.
Tilt it so that not too much melts but it also doesn't burn out (a place with no air movement helps).
Let the PLA drop on different places to let it cool down and you don't deform/melt your part (small parts are tricky) Model choice & print settings:
Choose some rather big part with no intricate geometries (vases etc)
Print with thick walls so it wont deform from the heat .
Print with thick layers since the coat will smooth out everything anyway. NOTE:
The finish is very smooth but not very flat.
It might have some microscopic bubbles in it when it burnt too long before dropping.
Light colors might show discoloration ( artistic use possible )
You might mix different colors :)
Due to thermal overexposure its more brittle than the base material :( SECURITY:
  • Only do this in an completely fireproof (and vented) environment at best outside.
  • Absolute keep the droplets away from skin. Nasty burns come in an instant.
  • Take caution the droplets can continue burning after falling.
    They are so hot that they might even ignite paper.
    They certainly scorch paper thus quartz sand would be optimal as base.
    I AM NOT RESPONSIBLE IF YOU BURN DOWN YOUR PLACE

description.text:
I have an after-market "Kreg style" pocket hole jig that uses a thumbscrew to secure the board into the jig. One of the things I liked with the Kreg was the toggle clamp to hold the board. I designed this clamp to upgrade my pocket hole jig. You could use this clamp for any light-duty push-pull clamping solution. The barrel is tapped with a 1/4" - 20 thread to fit the carriage bolt shown. The rest of the nuts and bolts are #6-32. Here is a production version of a similar style clamp made of metal:
http://industrialcomponentsgroup.com/toggle-clamps-push-pull/push-pull-toggle-clamps

Print all the plastic parts, I used ABS plastic.  
Sand mating surfaces for tight, clean fit.  
Tap barrel with 1/4-20 tap.  
Finish (I used acetone vapor method)  
Insert barrel in clamp then glue into square base with cyanoacrylate (super glue).  
Bolt remaining parts together  
Insert 1/4-20 carriage bolt with adjustment nut into barrel.  
Enjoy.  
Comments and remixes welcome.

Attach the workpiece to a base piece of wood and mill lower.stl. lower.stl contains two holes to help position the wood when cutting upper.stl. description.text:
Complete Frame Mounting System for the i3 / Duplicator style of 3d printer.

<<<

Because of a death in my family, I will not be able to work on this project for a while. I am not abandoning it, I Promise. Thank you to all who have liked this and are printing it.

<<<<

The first picture is the finished project. The next four pictures show the range of motion for the hot end carriage.

This mod has 56 parts, so far. It requires a lot of 3 mm bolts from 12 mm up to 20 mm in thread length, 2 4 mm bolts that are 20 mm long, and 2 2 mm bolts that are 12 mm long..

There is no drilling required. It eliminates the power box and the wiring umbilical.

It improves the frame rigidness considerably. It adds 60 mm clearance at the top of the frame, so the hot end can print to the full 180 mm without hitting.

It eliminates the drag chain from the right Z axis motor to the X axis mount above. It adds a drag chain to the hot bed, to reduce strain on the wiring.

It features an adjustable Z switch mount and Z plunger mount.

description.text:
This is a replica of the CR10 extruder arm. These arms often break and it's always a good idea to have an extra one laying around.
